00:07:40.090 --> 00:07:43.560
And all of that inspired us.

00:07:43.560 --> 00:07:47.190
&gt;&gt; John Rocco: That was great, Sherri.

00:07:47.190 --> 00:07:49.330
&gt;&gt; Sherri Duskey Rinker: Thanks, John.

00:07:49.330 --> 00:07:54.570
&gt;&gt; John Rocco: So I want to talk to you a
little bit about how Virginia Lee Burton went

00:07:54.570 --> 00:08:00.350
about creating books because in the process
of making this book I was very inspired by

00:08:00.350 --> 00:08:04.300
how she made the pictures and how she designed
the book.

00:08:04.300 --> 00:08:08.790
This is a page from her book "Choo Choo."

00:08:08.790 --> 00:08:13.760
And if you look on the left-hand side, you
can see the text.

00:08:13.760 --> 00:08:16.410
And on the right-hand side, you see the picture.

00:08:16.410 --> 00:08:20.460
Now she made these books a long, long time
ago.

00:08:20.460 --> 00:08:24.380
Eighty -- almost 80 years ago or more.

00:08:24.380 --> 00:08:25.490
Some of them.

00:08:25.490 --> 00:08:31.840
And so there wasn't a precedent -- there wasn't
so many ways to make children's books.

00:08:31.840 --> 00:08:32.870
Usually, it was, okay.

00:08:32.870 --> 00:08:34.060
The words go on one side.

00:08:34.060 --> 00:08:35.849
The picture goes on the other.

00:08:35.849 --> 00:08:38.150
And in this case, she did that as well.

00:08:38.150 --> 00:08:41.029
But you see how she laid out the words?

00:08:41.029 --> 00:08:46.710
Do you see how the train is moving from the
city to the country?

00:08:46.710 --> 00:08:50.170
And how it's winding its way over those hills?

00:08:50.170 --> 00:08:54.380
She decided to emulate that movement with
the words.

00:08:54.380 --> 00:08:58.080
And that helped tell the story.

00:08:58.080 --> 00:09:04.310
And as you read her books, you'll see that
this kind of design would go into all of her

00:09:04.310 --> 00:09:05.560
books.

00:09:05.560 --> 00:09:12.350
In this book which is about "Katy and the
Big Snow," you can see that she incorporated

00:09:12.350 --> 00:09:15.450
the text into the picture.

00:09:15.450 --> 00:09:16.460
So I'll read it.

00:09:16.460 --> 00:09:21.220
Then after she had found the broken down truck
plows, she started home.

00:09:21.220 --> 00:09:23.730
^M00:09:21 The fire department had put out
the fire.

00:09:23.730 --> 00:09:26.320
And there you see the fire trucks.

00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:28.310
The doctor had saved his patient.

00:09:28.310 --> 00:09:30.490
And you see the little ambulance.

00:09:30.490 --> 00:09:34.190
The water department had repaired the main.

00:09:34.190 --> 00:09:36.420
The telephone and electricity were on.

00:09:36.420 --> 00:09:38.130
The mail could go through.

00:09:38.130 --> 00:09:40.620
And the police could protect the city.

00:09:40.620 --> 00:09:42.670
Thanks to what Katy did.

00:09:42.670 --> 00:09:46.050
So you see how the text and the image work
together?

00:09:46.050 --> 00:09:48.920
They're almost in this dance.

00:09:48.920 --> 00:09:53.850
That's one of the incredible things that Virginia
Lee Burton brought to children's books.

00:09:53.850 --> 00:09:58.110
It was no longer about text on one side, picture
on the other.

00:09:58.110 --> 00:10:03.390
She started to integrate the words and the
pictures to help tell her story.

00:10:03.390 --> 00:10:09.070
You can see from this image from "Maybelle
the Cable Car" how the words actually connect

00:10:09.070 --> 00:10:14.430
the two drawings into one bigger shape or
bigger design.

00:10:14.430 --> 00:10:16.730
No hill too step for Maybelle.

00:10:16.730 --> 00:10:20.120
No matter what the weather -- wet or dry -- she
could not slip.

00:10:20.120 --> 00:10:21.490
She had her grip.

00:10:21.490 --> 00:10:23.190
And three kinds of brakes besides.

00:10:23.190 --> 00:10:24.940
"Ting, ting, ting."

00:10:24.940 --> 00:10:29.540
And you can see this image.

00:10:29.540 --> 00:10:33.980
You might be familiar from "Mike Mulligan
and the Steam Shovel" where Mary Ann, the

00:10:33.980 --> 00:10:37.230
steam shovel, is just digging away at the
dirt.

00:10:37.230 --> 00:10:38.790
And there's smoke flying.

00:10:38.790 --> 00:10:41.560
And there's steam coming out of the engine.

00:10:41.560 --> 00:10:48.670
So you can see how she used patterns and designs
to create this circular motion.

00:10:48.670 --> 00:10:53.260
And not only does it create a sense of motion
but it creates a sense of energy.

00:10:53.260 --> 00:10:59.600
You can see how strong and powerful Mary Ann
is as she digs away at that hole with just

00:10:59.600 --> 00:11:02.940
the sun peeking out from the clouds.

00:11:02.940 --> 00:11:07.500
And you can see this kind of patterning in
the book "The Little House."

00:11:07.500 --> 00:11:09.940
You see the clouds going across the sky.

00:11:09.940 --> 00:11:10.940
A little cloud.

00:11:10.940 --> 00:11:12.110
A little bit bigger cloud.

00:11:12.110 --> 00:11:13.740
An even bigger cloud.

00:11:13.740 --> 00:11:15.000
And a bigger cloud.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:16.620
Same with the trees.

00:11:16.620 --> 00:11:21.709
And you can see these overlapping shapes that
help make the image.

00:11:21.709 --> 00:11:26.250
Now the wonderful thing about the little house,
if you look at it again -- and I had this

00:11:26.250 --> 00:11:32.050
experience as a kid when I looked at the book
"The Little House" which was that the house,

00:11:32.050 --> 00:11:38.140
itself, never moves as you turn the page from
this page to this page.

00:11:38.140 --> 00:11:40.390
Nothing happens to the house.

00:11:40.390 --> 00:11:42.020
It stays in the same spot.

00:11:42.020 --> 00:11:44.550
It's the same size.

00:11:44.550 --> 00:11:47.950
And the world around the house keeps changing.

00:11:47.950 --> 00:11:51.640
And that was the one of the incredible things
because it was almost like,, what's going

00:11:51.640 --> 00:11:52.640
on here?

00:11:52.640 --> 00:11:57.450
The house, which is what the story's about,
is right there in the center.

00:11:57.450 --> 00:11:59.560
And everything around it is changing.

00:11:59.560 --> 00:12:01.680
And that book is about change.

00:12:01.680 --> 00:12:06.730
When Virginia Lee Burton and her husband first
bought their home in Folley Cove, they actually

00:12:06.730 --> 00:12:10.070
picked it up and moved it away from the road.

00:12:10.070 --> 00:12:13.750
And I think that was the inspiration for this
book.

00:12:13.750 --> 00:12:18.130
Was the idea that we don't want to be so close
to everything that's happening.

00:12:18.130 --> 00:12:20.580
We want to be back a little bit.

00:12:20.580 --> 00:12:23.160
And that's what eventually happens with the
little house in the book.

00:12:23.160 --> 00:12:28.860
They pick it up and they move it back to the
country as the city built up around it.

